2\. Menu structure

  


Requirements

All documents and reports will be organized into a hierarchical menu composed of logical sections. This menu will be accessible via phone or fax cover sheet, and can be maintained by an online interface accessible to an administrator.

  


Each folder can contain one of the following kinds of documents:

  * Compass reports
  * Quickbooks reports
  * Uploaded documents
    * Checklists
    * Shed drawings
    * Faxed-in documents

Permissions

Individual folders or files may each have unique permissions. These permissions may be a whitelist (only certain users/groups have permission) or a blacklist (everyone except certain users/groups have permission.) File-level permissions can further restrict permissions, but if a user cannot access a given folder, they will not be able to access any files within that folder.

  


The software will support configuring a folder to allow a user to retrieve documents out of the folder, but not store new ones.

  


Administration

The administrator will be able to modify the folder structure via an online interface. Additionally, other users can be designated as administrators, which would give access to the entire menu structure, including viewing menu entries (but not content) that they would not otherwise have access to. This menu structure report will display the menu items in a tree structure.

  


Administrators will be able to view a version of the menu that displays permissions and visibility.

  


The online interface will have tools to view and modify the permissions for a given user in the context of the phone menu. Additionally, on each document there will be a link to a report showing which users have permission to access the document.

  


PIN-protected folders

Each user will have a PIN. Folders can be marked as being PIN-protected. For these folders, the user will have to enter their PIN to gain access to any documents inside the folder.

  


Faxed-in documents

A document can be stored via fax. When storing, the user can specify an existing document number, which will overwrite the existing document, or a new document number. If a document with that access number already exists, the user will be prompted to make sure that they want to overwrite it. See subsequent sections for details on how this is accomplished in both interfaces.

  


Activity reports

Fax users designated as administrators will receive a daily log of all send/receive activity in the system at 3:00AM. This will include all documents stored or retrieved, and will include the user, the document name, and the date/time.

Uploader

  


Folders

  * Admin defines folders. Each folder has an optional parent, and an access #.
    * Parent droplist is a mini-tree structure of folders (but only ones that don't have files.)
  * Access control can be blacklist or whitelist
    * Builder (user), Company (group), or everyone
    * Each setting can be either read or write.
  * Each folder designated as a "type":
    * Uploads
    * Quickbooks reports
    * Compass reports
  * Each folder will have an ID (used for batch uploader, for example)
  * Has deleted flag.
  * Prevent deletion if there are child documents. Prevent setting the deleted flag if there are child documents that are not deleted.
  * Validate that the access # has the right number of digits.
  * Boolean whether the folder is PIN-protected.



  


Documents

  * Have a document record.
    * Could be an uploaded document, a QB document/shed drawing, or a Compass "virtual" document.
    * Tied to a parent folder.
    * Access control can be blacklist or whitelist
      * Builder (user), Company (group), or everyone
    * Has a link to an activity report (transmission records below)
    * For uploaded/QB documents, has one or more File records pointing to it.
    * For Compass reports, has the name of the report in Compass and the parameters to ask for.
    * Can optionally have additional visibility restrictions? I don't like this, but we may have to do it.
    * Whether to send the document in color, if the recipient supports it.
  * Record type can't change
  * Have a quick way to send a document to an email/fax # (with a person droplist)
  * Has deleted flag.
  * Validate that the menu access # has the right number of digits.



  


File record

  * ID (random string)
  * # pages
  * Quality (Low, Medium, High, Original)
  * Creation date
  * Creator



  


Transmission record

  * Records any time anything happens to documents
    * User uploaded document
      * Points to document record
      * Points to file record
      * Fax duration
    * User requested document
      * Points to document record (or transmission record, for replays)
    * User requested report
      * Contains parameters
      * Points to generated file record
      * Compass duration
      * Fax duration
    * As a special case, queues activity that we want to make happen.
  * Boolean whether the document was PIN-protected(?)
  * Fax #, email address, or store (for later download)
  * Phone # blank to indicate the software (either sender or recipient)
  * Date/time
  * Request details:
    * For interactive, the user
    * For batch, the batch job ID
    * For phone, the menu sequence
    * For cover sheets, the interpreted instructions (for later development/testing)



  


User record

  * (This is really just an addition to the current user profile detail screen.)
  * One or more groups that the user is a part of.



  


WSGI entrypoint

  * S3 access:
    * Each looks in the DB to see if you should have access to that record.
    * /doc/<docid>/<fileid>
    * /job/<jobid>
    * /upload/doc/<docid>/<fileid> -> validates access, disallows overwrite.
